{"questionId":"15614","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the function&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"f\\left( x \\right) = {x^3} - 5{x^2} + 6x - 3 + \\frac{1}{x}\">\n  <mi>f</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>3</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>5</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>6</mn>\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>3</mn>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x > 0\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>&gt;</mo>\n  <mn>0</mn>\n</math></span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The function <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"f\\left( x \\right) = {x^3} - 5{x^2} + 6x - 3 + \\frac{1}{x}\">\n  <mi>f</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>3</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>5</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>6</mn>\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>3</mn>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x > 0\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>&gt;</mo>\n  <mn>0</mn>\n</math></span>, models the path of a river, as shown on the&nbsp;following map, where both axes represent distance and are measured in kilometres. On the&nbsp;same map, the location of a highway is defined by the function <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"g\\left( x \\right) = 0.5{\\left( 3 \\right)^{ - x}} + 1\">\n  <mi>g</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>0.5</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mrow>\n        <mo>(</mo>\n        <mn>3</mn>\n        <mo>)</mo>\n      </mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mo>−</mo>\n        <mi>x</mi>\n      </mrow>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1</mn>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/59a954cda6efe17cc462afb00f9321f17c483da6.png\"></p>\n<p>The origin, O(0, 0) , is the location of the centre of a town called Orangeton.</p>\n<p>A straight footpath, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"P\">\n  <mi>P</mi>\n</math></span>, is built to connect the centre of Orangeton to the river at the point&nbsp;where <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x = \\frac{1}{2}\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the function, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"P\\left( x \\right)\">\n  <mi>P</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> , that would define this footpath on the map.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{0 - \\frac{7}{8}}}{{0 - \\frac{1}{2}}}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>0</mn>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mfrac>\n        <mn>7</mn>\n        <mn>8</mn>\n      </mfrac>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>0</mn>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mfrac>\n        <mn>1</mn>\n        <mn>2</mn>\n      </mfrac>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for correct substitution into gradient formula. Accept equivalent forms such as <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{7}{8} = \\frac{1}{2}m\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>7</mn>\n    <mn>8</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mi>m</mi>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{7}{4}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>7</mn>\n    <mn>4</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>&nbsp; (1.75)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)</strong></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"P\\left( x \\right) = \\frac{7}{4}x\\,\\,\\left( {1.75x} \\right)\">\n  <mi>P</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>7</mn>\n    <mn>4</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>1.75</mn>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)<em>(G3)</em></strong></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Follow through from part (a).</p>\n<p><strong><em>[3 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"15614","referenceCode":"19M.2.SL.TZ1.T_4b.i","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the function, P ( x ) , that would define this footpath on the map.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.2—Functions, notation domain, range and inverse as reflection","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.4—Key features of graphs, intersections using technology"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}